/*
  # Harden `leads` RLS — remove always-true write policies

  ## Why
  The security advisor flagged three "RLS Policy Always True" warnings on
  `public.leads`:
    - insert_leads  (INSERT, anon)          — WITH CHECK (true)
    - update_leads  (UPDATE, authenticated) — USING (true) WITH CHECK (true)
    - delete_leads  (DELETE, authenticated) — USING (true)

  None of these are needed by the application:
    - The public lead form does NOT write with the anon key. It POSTs to the
      `notify-lead` Edge Function, which inserts using the SERVICE ROLE key and
      bypasses RLS. So `insert_leads` (anon) is dead weight that let anyone with
      the public anon key spam rows straight into the table.
    - There is no in-app admin UI that updates or deletes leads, so
      `update_leads` / `delete_leads` are unused. The owner manages leads in the
      Supabase dashboard, which uses the service role and bypasses RLS anyway.

  ## What this does
  Drops the three always-true write policies. RLS stays ENABLED, so the anon and
  authenticated roles now have NO write access through the API — exactly what we
  want. The lead form is unaffected (service-role edge function).

  The `select_leads` (SELECT, authenticated) policy is intentionally left in
  place: it was not flagged, and a logged-in owner reading the leads list is the
  intended behavior.
*/

DROP POLICY IF EXISTS "insert_leads" ON leads;
DROP POLICY IF EXISTS "update_leads" ON leads;
DROP POLICY IF EXISTS "delete_leads" ON leads;
